                        <h2> kjhg</h2>
                      <br>The Handbook for the Recently Diagnosed Schizo, or "A New Communication Protocol and How it Feels Without a Primer."</br>
                     <br>  </br>
                    I sat at the firepit tonight and turned and saw a cloud covering the moon in the shape of a Y. It hovered over it briefly.
                    Long enough for me to add it to my "well, that was interesting" list. One of many things I never write about it. All of it together
                    sounds bananas. I wrote in my personal journal a long time ago to press Y to join my game. I should have written "ask why" to join my game.
                  
                  I've heard things like "You have no idea what is going on," and while that may be 1000% percent true, I know what I experienced up to this point. 
                  
                  Of course I do not. I know nothing. I know what I lived or experienced or spent time learning and that is all.
                  
                  Suffice to say,                   
                   I imagine the way I feel
                    would be the way a lot of people would feel if they were to experience always on 24/7 communications without a primer or any type 
                    of communication about what it is or what it's for. 
                    
                    I am of sane mind and body and I am about to write about some put on your tin foil hat stuff. 
                    But more like, what would you think or do if it happened to you?

                    For me, a librarian and a writer, everything is just content. and discovery. And things to catalog or think about or write about. 
                    
                    The bad and the good. And all the weird stuff in between.
                    
                    I have been hearing not voices, but an overlay on top of existing sound since August of last year, so 7+ months now.
                    It's amplified by very large machine noises and impossible to ignore. I have to put headphones on to get any sort of focus because
                    they never shut the fuck up.
                    
                    I thought it was a military application perhaps and maybe it is, but now I think, well maybe it's a new communication channel.
                    That you are? or are not? supposed to write about? That's the moral question for me. The reason why I didn't want to say anything. It could be very useful
                    for a lot of military applications, but it's more broad use is for civilian use, not for special operations.
                    
                    And nobody told me I wasn't allowed to write about it. 
                    
                    And no one listens to me anyway.
                    
                    And if they didn't want me to write about it, they'd find a way to stop me. Just thinking out loud my logical thought about it.
                    
                    No one is allowed to say these types of things out loud, because it's too bananas and too far out for them to even imagine, let alone experience.
                    
                    You'd lose all credibility and someone would photo shop a tin foil hat on your noggin. Don't worry, I already tried to block it with tin foil. It does not work.
                    
                    A good scientist and writer does not care about looking foolish.
                    
                    Exhaust all possibilities until you arrive at a slimmer set of data to deconstruct.
                    
                    
                    You have to keep it in the realm of science fiction for it to make sense or be "believable" to others. Why? So much is already possible. NOW.
                    
                    It's not that I don't care anymore about optics, it's that I want to SHARE what I experienced with others because of the implications it has for broader society.
                    
                    Imagine talking to someone without saying a word. That is what I wrote in 2021 about how I would connect with my husband at the time. We could speak without talking.
                    Not literally, but you know what I mean.
                    
                    But that is NOT what I mean here. I literally mean speaking without talking. 
                    
                    Maybe because I already wrote about it before, maybe that's why me. 
                    
                    I've been treating it as if it were a battle or thing to overcome because no one explained anything to me.
                    I WAS and felt assaulted psychologically.
                    
                    Constantly under pressure just to act normal and continue to live. Fighting for every day just to stay here.
                    
                    But this overcoming the "bad guy" thing - that's not the most interesting story. And it's lazy storytelling and it's boring!!
                    
                    There's nothing outside of current existing technology to prohibit the idea that you could talk to people through an intermediary layer of sound through electronic
                    devices or sound/vibrations that are not being deployed for harm but for comms only.

